│ This is an interesting bug. The `globalopt` pass is          │
│ attempting a clever optimization: if a global pointer is     │
│ only ever checked for nullness, it can be replaced by a      │
│ boolean global. This saves space and can enable further      │
│ optimizations. However, the pass fails to consider the       │
│ atomicity of the original pointer operations.                │
│                                                              │
│ When it transforms an `atomic` pointer load/store into an    │
│ operation on the new boolean global, it preserves the        │
│ atomicity, resulting in `atomic load i1` and `atomic store   │
│ i1`. These are invalid in LLVM IR because atomic operations  │
│ must act on types with a size that is a power of two bytes.  │
│ The verifier correctly flags this as an error and aborts.    │
│                                                              │
