│ The bug is caused by the `globalopt` pass incorrectly trying │
│ to optimize an atomic global pointer. The optimization       │
│ attempts to replace the pointer with a boolean (`i1`) if     │
│ it's only used in null comparisons. This transformation,     │
│ however, preserves the atomicity of the original load and    │
│ store operations. This leads to the creation of `atomic load │
│ i1` and `atomic store i1` instructions, which are invalid in │
│ LLVM IR because atomic operations must have a size that is a │
│ power-of-two number of bytes. The LLVM verifier detects this │
│ invalid IR and aborts compilation.                           │
│                                                              │
│ The fix is to prevent this pointer-to-boolean optimization   │
│ from being applied to atomic global variables. I will add a  │
│ check, `!GV->isAtomic()`, to the condition that guards this  │
│ transformation. This ensures that only non-atomic globals    │
│ are considered for this optimization, thus avoiding the      │
│ creation of illegal atomic operations on `i1` types.         │
│                                                              │
│ I will now apply this change.                                │
│                                                              │
